<div class="comment-wrapper"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d53b7c5f9b5f5557b9082face9b632a0?s=50"></div><header><strong>[Review] SE-0060: Enforcing order of defaulted parameters</strong> from <string>Dave Abrahams</string> &lt;dabrahams at apple.com&gt;<p>May  5, 2016 at 06:00:00pm</p></header><div class="content"><p>on Wed May 04 2016, Erica Sadun &lt;swift-evolution at swift.org&gt; wrote:<br></p><p>&gt; Having to figure out where a previously defaulted value should be inserted when<br>&gt; adding an explicit setting imposes an undue burden on the programmer, reduces<br>&gt; flexibility during experimentation, and removes one of the neatest Swift<br>&gt; features. For this reason, I vote no on the proposal. By rejecting this<br>&gt; proposal, Swift retains a flexibility that defers to the programmer, placing the<br>&gt; programmer&#39;s needs before any benefits that may accrue to the compiler.<br>&gt;<br>&gt; I have followed the discussion. I believe it goes against the general Swift<br>&gt; philosophy. And while the change being proposed is significant to be part of a<br>&gt; formal language review process, I think adopting it would be the wrong thing to<br>&gt; do.<br>&gt;<br>&gt; -- Erica<br></p><p>FWIW, Erica echoes my instincts on the topic.<br></p><p>-- <br>Dave<br></p></div></li></ul></div>    </main>
